function extract_model_names(abstracts) {
  models = [];
  for (let abstract of abstracts) {
    if (abstract.indexOf("GDE-based") >= 0) {
      let match = undefined;
      const regex = /AdvancedCalc/gi;
      while ((match = regex.exec(abstract)) !== null) {
        models.push(match[0]);
      }
    }
  }
  return models;
}
```
This function iterates through each abstract in the list. If a string contains "GDE-based", it uses a regular expression to search for and extract words that match "AdvancedCalc". The regular expression `g` flags make it match globally (in any case), `i` flags make it ignore case differences, and `c` makes it recognize camelCase as word boundaries. Once all occurrences are found, the function populates its output array with the model names.

You can use this in an environment like R or Python with libraries like R caret or scikit-learn. For example:
```
models <- extract_model_names(c("This abstract is devoted to GDE-based systems such as AdvancedCalc.", "Abstracts solely devoted on \"AdvancedCalc\" system should be discarded."));
models # will return: [["AdvancedCalc"]]
```
